\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The vast majority of Active Galactic Nuclei (AGN) are obscured by thick
 columns of gas and dust.
 X-ray surveys over the last decade indicate that 
\begin_inset Formula $20-40\%$
\end_inset

 are hidden behind Compton-thick column densities (
\begin_inset Formula $\NH\apprge10^{24}\text{cm}^{-2}$
\end_inset

) and of the remaining population, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim75\%$
\end_inset

 are obscured with 
\begin_inset Formula $\NH=10^{22}-10^{24}\text{cm}^{-2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "Treister2004,Brightman2014,Ueda2014,Buchner2015,Aird2015"

\end_inset

 at the peak of AGN activity at redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.5-3$
\end_inset

.
 An open question is whether the same gas reservoir is responsible for fuelling
 the AGN by accretion onto Supermassive Black Holes (SMBHs), and whether
 it itself is affected by AGN activity.
 To address this, the first step is to identify the scale at which the obscuring
 gas resides.
 Traditionally, AGN obscuration is associated with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

torus
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, a nuclear (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim10\text{pc}$
\end_inset

) structure around the accretion disk.
 Many basic questions about this gas reservoir remain to be answered, including
 its density, substructure and stability mechanism 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Elitzur2006a,Hoenig2013"

\end_inset

.
 Assuming sampling from random viewing angles, the high fraction of obscured
 AGN implies large covering fractions.
 Therefore turbulent structures such as winds from accretion disks have
 been invoked.
 However, for the covering fractions to be useful constraints for torus
 models, the importance of galaxy-scale gas to the obscuration has to be
 estimated.
 Separating the covering and column densities from nuclear and galaxy-scale
 obscurers is the goal of this work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Local galaxies exemplify that several scales can contribute to the obscured
 columns.
 The Milky Way gas distribution shows column densities of 
\begin_inset Formula $\NH>10^{22}\text{cm}^{-2}$
\end_inset

, but only in very low Galactic latitudes (
\begin_inset Formula $|b|\apprle2\text{°}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Dickey1990,Kalberla2005GalNHdist"

\end_inset

).
 Towards the Galactic Center columns with 
\begin_inset Formula $\NH>10^{24}\text{cm}^{-2}$
\end_inset

 can be found in the Central Molecular Zone 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Morris1996,Molinari2011"

\end_inset

 and in the equivalent central zones of nearby AGN host galaxies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Prieto2014"

\end_inset

.
 Also the obscuration in the AGN host galaxy NGC
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

1068 is clearly nuclear (in this work: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim100\text{pc}$
\end_inset

 or smaller), because its Compton-thick column is observed in a face-on
 galaxy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Matt1997a"

\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, many nearby, obscured AGN are hosted in edge-on galaxies
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Maiolino1995"

\end_inset

, which suggests that dust-lanes may also be important obscurers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "for galactic optical/infrared extinction"
before "see also"
key "Goulding2009"

\end_inset

.
 Hence 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Matt2000"

\end_inset

 proposed a two-phase model for the obscuration of AGN: a central, nuclear
 obscurer which provides Compton-thick obscuration, and the host galaxy,
 which provides mildly obscured lines of sight.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Some obscured AGN are clearly unobscured in other lines-of-sight.
 The strongest evidence for this comes from cones of ionised gas which show
 the Thomson-scattered spectra of unobscured AGN 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Antonucci1982"

\end_inset

.
 The inner obscurer thus must leave some lines-of-sight (LOS) unobscured.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the Milky Way and local galaxies are limited in their use as templates
 for the high-redshift universe, specifically at peak SMBH growth (
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.5-3$
\end_inset

; e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Aird2010"

\end_inset

).
 At that time, the gas content in galaxies was probably higher, as indicated
 by molecular gas measurements 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "Tacconi2013"

\end_inset

 which perhaps lead to the peak of star formation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "see review by"
key "Madau2014"

\end_inset

 and the increase in the fraction of obscured AGN with redshift 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "Treister2004,Ueda2014,Buchner2015"

\end_inset

.
 The efficient growth of SMBHs at these early epochs has been attributed
 to galaxy mergers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ciotti_Ostriker2001"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Thus ultra-luminous infrared galaxies (ULIRGs) in the local Universe, which
 show strong star formation and signs of strong distortions, may be better
 analogues for high-redshift AGN host galaxies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Sanders1988,Lonsdale2006"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

In the semi-empirical model of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hopkins2006OriginModel"

\end_inset

, the merging of galaxies makes gas available for both star formation and
 SMBH growth, leading to an initially long obscured phase followed by a
 short, bright AGN feedback phase which removes the obscuring gas.
 In the most extreme simulations, AGN feedback removes a high fraction of
 the global galactic gas, leaving behind a red and dead elliptical without
 subsequent star formation or SMBH growth 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DiMatteo2005,Springel2005"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

This model was expanded by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hopkins2006OriginModel"

\end_inset

 to reproduce local scaling relationships between galaxy components and
 SMBH masses, the luminosity function of AGN, the fraction of active galaxies,
 and the obscuration dichotomy of AGN.
 The evolutionary model also explains why bright AGN are less frequently
 found to be mildly obscured than faint AGN 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ueda2003,Silverman2008,Ebrero2009,Ueda2014,Buchner2015,Aird2015"

\end_inset

, albeit only qualitatively 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hopkins2005,Hopkins2006OriginModel"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The evolutionary model of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hopkins2006OriginModel"

\end_inset

 lead many researchers to investigate the fraction of obscured AGN in mergers
 using a variety of techniques, with mixed success 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Grogin2003,Grogin2005,Pierce2007,Gabor2009,Grogin2011a,Kocevski2011,Kocevski2012,Treister2012,Glikman2015,Kocevski2015"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

In this work we investigate the obscuring role of galaxy-scale gas in the
 transition from obscured AGN in gas-rich galaxies to unobscured AGN in
 gas-poor galaxies, as proposed in the evolutionary sequence of that model.
 To effectively decouple the galaxy-scale and nuclear X-ray obscurer, we
 need to go beyond a single, central source.
\end_layout

