\begin_layout Section
Methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Methodology"

\end_inset

Our goal is to predict the fraction of obscured AGN from the obscuration
 of host galaxy-scale gas alone, i.e.
 without nuclear obscuration (the torus and central molecular zones).
 In this fashion we will be able to separate the large-scale and small-scale
 obscurer.
 In Paper I we established a relation between the distribution of X-ray
 absorbing column densities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\NH$
\end_inset

, in galaxies and the stellar mass of the galaxy.
 It follows approximately a normal distribution around 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\NH=10^{21.7}\text{cm}^{-2}\times\left(M_{\star}/10^{9.5}M_{\odot}\right)^{1/3}\label{eq:NHM-rel}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with standard deviation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=0.5\,\text{dex}$
\end_inset

.
 This 
\begin_inset Formula $\NH-M_{\star}$
\end_inset

 relation was derived using an unbiased sample of long Gamma Ray Bursts
 (LGRBs)
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
 and is depicted in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:MNH-rel"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Because the obscuration is host mass dependent, the obscurer is arguably
 the host galaxy itself.
 In Paper I we show that modern cosmological hydro-dynamic simulations reproduce
 absorption by galaxy-scale metal gas and predict 
\begin_inset Formula $\NH-M_{\star}$
\end_inset

 relations very similar to Equation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NHM-rel"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We apply this relation to the AGN host galaxy population to estimate host
 galaxy obscuration.
 This relation was derived from actively star forming galaxies, therefore
 a caveat is that results may slightly over-represent the galaxy gas present
 in AGN host galaxies which have average 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Rosario2011,Rosario2013,Santini2012"

\end_inset

 or even below-average 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Mullaney2015"

\end_inset

 star formation rates.
 The major benefit of using this relationship is that it is based on the
 same observable as AGN obscured fractions, namely the photo-electric absorption
 of X-rays.
 Paper I also investigated the host galaxy metallicity bias of LGRB and
 concluded that it has a negligible effect on the obscurer.
 Local galaxies are also shown there to follow the 
\begin_inset Formula $\NH-M_{\star}$
\end_inset

 relation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with the stellar mass function (SMF) of the galaxy population.
 Its shape 
\begin_inset Formula $P(M_{\star}|z)$
\end_inset

 is approximately a Schechter function and was measured by e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Muzzin2013"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Ilbert2013"

\end_inset

 out to 
\begin_inset Formula $z\sim4$
\end_inset

.
 Then we populate the galaxies with AGN.
 The occupation probability 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\text{AGN}|M_{\star},z)$
\end_inset

 has been measured by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Aird2012"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bongiorno2012"

\end_inset

 primarily for the redshift interval 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.5-2$
\end_inset

.
 More accurately, these authors measure the specific accretion rate distribution
 (SARD), 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\LX|M_{\star},z)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\LX$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $2-10\,\text{keV}$
\end_inset

 X-ray luminosity.
 They find factorised powerlaw relationships of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\LX|M_{\star},z)=A\cdot L_{{\rm X}}^{\gamma_{L}}\cdot M_{\star}^{\gamma_{M}}\cdot(1+z)^{\gamma_{z}}$
\end_inset

.
 At the highest luminosities, an Eddington limit is required to explain
 the steep decrease in the luminosity function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Aird2013"

\end_inset

.
 In this work, however, we focus on the luminosity range 
\begin_inset Formula $\LX=10^{42-45}\text{erg/s}$
\end_inset

 regime and thus use only the observed relation.
 The final ingredient is the obscuring column density distribution (CDD)
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\NH|M_{\star})$
\end_inset

, which is given by Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NHM-rel"

\end_inset

 as a normal distribution in 
\begin_inset Formula $\log\NH$
\end_inset

.
 We assume that the galaxy-scale gas is independent of nuclear activity
 for individual galaxies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The obscured fraction can then be simply computed by Monte Carlo simulations.
 Analytically we can put the three distributions together as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(\NH,\LX,M_{\star}|z)=\underbrace{P(M_{\star}|z)}_{\text{SMF}}\times\underbrace{P(\LX|M_{\star},z)}_{\text{SARD}}\times\underbrace{P(\NH|M_{\star})}_{\text{Eq 1}}\label{eq:combination}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

After inserting the factorised powerlaw relationship of the SARD, the result
 has the form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(\NH,\LX,M_{\star}|z)=A\times L_{X}^{\gamma_{L}}\times f(M_{\star}|z)\times P(\NH|M_{\star}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

While the absolute probability of finding an AGN is a function of luminosity,
 the mass distribution is independent of luminosity.
 That is, at every luminosity (not considering the Eddington limit), the
 same mix of host stellar masses contribute.
 Therefore, the implication is that the galaxy-scale gas obscuration is
 the same at all AGN luminosities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We adopt an AGN definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\LX>10^{42}\text{erg/s}$
\end_inset

.
 The frequency distribution of column densities 
\begin_inset Formula $\NH$
\end_inset

 for the AGN population is then computed by integrating over stellar mass
 and luminosity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P(\NH|z)=\int\int_{10^{42}\text{erg/s}}^{\infty}P(\NH,\LX,M_{\star}|z)\,d\LX\,dM_{\star}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally the obscured AGN fraction is the cumulative distribution, i.e.
 the frequency of AGN being covered by a certain column density threshold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\NH$
\end_inset

 or higher: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{\text{cov}}(>\NH)=\int_{\NH}^{\infty}P(\NH'|z)d\NH'.\label{eq:fcov}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Into the calculation of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\text{cov}}$
\end_inset

 we propagate the uncertainties from the obscuration relation for Paper
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

I.
 We consider two SMF (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Muzzin2013"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Ilbert2013"

\end_inset

) and two SARD measurements (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Aird2012"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Bongiorno2012"

\end_inset

), to incorporate systematic uncertainties.
 To summarise, we rely only on observational relations to predict the obscuratio
n of the AGN population by galaxy-scale gas.
\end_layout

