\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Ldep"

\end_inset

We can now discuss the luminosity-dependence of the obscurer.
 X-ray surveys consistently find a strong decline towards high luminosities
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ueda2003,Hasinger2005,LaFranca2005,Ebrero2009,Ueda2014,Buchner2015,Aird2015"

\end_inset

 of the obscured fraction 
\begin_inset Formula $\NH>10^{22}\,{\rm cm}^{-2}$
\end_inset

 in the Compton-thin AGN (CTNAGN) population.
 In Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:L-dep-sketch"

\end_inset

 we have sketched this decline from 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim70\%$
\end_inset

 to a persistent 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim40\%$
\end_inset

.
 According to our results, this can be interpreted as two scales contributing
 to the obscuration: a 
\begin_inset Formula $40\%$
\end_inset

 galaxy-scale obscurer, and a luminosity-dependent nuclear obscurer.
 The former is constrained from GRB observations (Paper
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

I), re-weighted to the mass distribution of AGN (results of this paper).
 The latter is the remainder to fit the observations.
 According to this picture, the nuclear obscurer completely disappears toward
 high luminosities at 
\begin_inset Formula $L(2-10\,{\rm keV})\approx10^{44.5}{\rm erg/s}$
\end_inset

.
 This luminosity is however redshift-dependent, with higher redshifts having
 higher cut-off luminosities.
 This has been found in many works 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Ueda2003,Ebrero2009,LaFranca2005,Ueda2014,Aird2015"

\end_inset

 by fitting a empirical, parametric model to the relative number density
 derived from AGN surveys.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Buchner2015"

\end_inset

 derived the same result using a non-parametric method, indicating that
 this is indeed a robust result.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Buchner2015"

\end_inset

, the implications for obscurer models were discussed in their Section 5.3.
 They concluded that an Eddington-limited blow-out of the obscurer could
 explain the luminosity dependence.
 As the luminosity dependence is observed to evolve, a black hole mass dependenc
e needed to be invoked.
 If the average, currently accreting black hole is more massive at high
 redshift than at low redshift, the turn-over luminosity decreases over
 cosmic time.
 Such black hole mass downsizing has evidence from optical observations
 of the black hole mass function evolution 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Schulze2010,Kelly2013a,Schulze2015"

\end_inset

 and semi-analytic models which reproduce the evolution of the AGN luminosity
 function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Fanidakis2012,Enoki2014,Hirschmann2014"

\end_inset

.
 Recently, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Oh2015"

\end_inset

