\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Physical-effects"

\end_inset

Physical processes giving rise to the luminosity and mass-dependent behaviour
 cannot be discussed rigorously within the scope of this paper.
 However, we point out a few key results of recent theoretical works.
 Otherwise we refer to the review of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hoenig2013"

\end_inset

 which discusses current torus modelling approaches.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We take note of the analytic wind model formalism described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Elitzur2016"

\end_inset

 and of the radiation-driven fountain model by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Wada2015"

\end_inset

.
 Both models produce a vertically extended obscurer structure as a function
 of luminosity and mass.
 At low luminosities, radiation is not sufficient to puff up the obscurer.
 In the hydro-dynamical simulations of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Wada2012"

\end_inset

 very high accretion luminosities are associated with strong outflows, which
 suppress the vertical extent of the obscuring structure as they occupy
 larger angles.
 The cartoon of Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Cartoon"

\end_inset

 illustrates such a possible wind scenario for the three, distinct obscuring
 components, with approximately the correct opening angles.
 For visualisation we have smooth gas distributions, while in reality the
 obscurer is thought to be clumpy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "and references therein"
before "see e.g.,"
key "Markowitz2014"

\end_inset

.
 To date, models of the nuclear obscurer largely lack observational constraints.
 Our PuffedTorus model summarises observational boundary constraints of
 covering fractions and column densities for how a physical 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

torus
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 model should behave.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A further, commonly overlooked aspect is the evolution of AGN.
 Faint AGN are much more common than luminous AGN 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "Barger2005,Ueda2003,Aird2010"

\end_inset

, a fact that has to be explained with the triggering and light-curve of
 accretion events.
 Galaxy-galaxy mergers are today thought to be the main trigger of luminous
 AGN activity, because SMBH need to accrete substantial fractions of their
 host galaxy gas (as shown by scaling relations), within durations comparable
 to dynamical timescales of galaxy centres 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Somerville2008"

\end_inset

.
 In the timeline proposed by Hopkins et al, the luminous phase occurs in
 relatively late merger phases.
 Luminous AGN stop further infall by radiation pressure and quickly reduce
 their column densities 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hopkins2006OriginModel"

\end_inset

.
 In contrast, the faint AGN population is suggested to be dominated by periods
 before and after peak accretion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hopkins2005LFinterpretation"

\end_inset

.
 Early merger phases may have enhanced obscuration, both galaxy-scale (Compton-t
hin) and nuclear (Compton-thin and Compton-thick) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Hopkins2005,Hopkins2006OriginModel"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, a substantial part of the faint AGN population is probably
 associated with secular triggering mechanisms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "Treister2012"

\end_inset

.
 One may therefore argue for a evolutionary AGN life [illustrative time
 share in brackets] consisting of 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
no accretion, and therefore no AGN detection [89%],
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
nearby gas leading to obscuration and triggering of a faint AGN [10%], either
 in the onset of a merger or due to secular events,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
major merger triggering a bright AGN, which immediately clears the vertically
 extended obscurer but shines for a period of time [1%] before fading.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such a duty cycle would give rise to the observed obscured fractions (Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:L-dep-sketch"

\end_inset

) while also respecting the luminosity function of AGN.
 To summarise, luminous AGN and faint AGN may live in different environments
 with different gas reservoirs feeding them; therefore unifying the obscuration
 properties of a luminosity-dependent torus may not be appropriate.
 
\end_layout

