\begin_layout Section
Cosmological hydro-dynamic simulations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Cosmological-simulations"

\end_inset

We now assess the gas content in simulated galaxies.
 Modern cosmological hydro-dynamic simulations self-consistently evolve
 galaxies and their processes (star formation, gas accretion, supernova
 and AGN feedback, etc.) in the context of well-constrained 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

CDM cosmologies.
 These simulations are constrained in their initial conditions to the baryon
 density available in the early Universe and are tuned to reproduce the
 local stellar mass functions.
 We consider two state-of-the-art cosmological hydro-dynamic simulations
 which also produce realistic galaxy morphologies.
 These simulations allow us to look at the spatial distribution of gas inside
 galaxies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Simulation sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Evolution and Assembly of Galaxies and their Environment (EAGLE) simulation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Schaye2015,Crain2015"

\end_inset

 reproduces many observed quantities; it reproduces very well the stellar
 mass function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Furlong2015a"

\end_inset

 and size distribution 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Furlong2015"

\end_inset

 of galaxies as a function of cosmic time, being tuned to reproduce these
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 Further relevant for this work it also produces galaxies with realistic
