\begin_layout Subsection
Methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We first investigate the gas distribution in the reference simulations.
 We focus on the metal component of gas as O and Fe are, for the relevant
 obscuring columns and redshifts, the most important elements for photo-electric
 absorption of X-rays.
 In galaxy evolution models, the massive end of the existing stellar population
 expels metals into the galaxy.
 The metal gas produced per stellar mass is determined by the chosen IMF
 and the metal yield, with the latter tuned to reproduce the stellar mass
 function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "Lu2015"

\end_inset

.
 The total metal gas mass residing in galaxies further depends on the chosen
 feedback models which can expel gas out of the galaxy.
 Typically the metal gas mass inside galaxies follows a 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{Z}:M_{\star}$
\end_inset

 ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $1:30$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $1:100$
\end_inset

 relation in semi-analytic models at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0-3$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "e.g."
key "Croton2006,Croton2016"

\end_inset

; Plots of these models can be found in Appendix
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


