\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 respectively, relative to the reference model.
 Here we find, surprisingly, that both models produce lower obscured fractions
 than the reference model.
 Strong feedback leads to underproduction of massive galaxies at 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\star}>10^{10.5}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "their Figure 10"
key "Crain2015"

\end_inset

, thereby biasing the galaxy population to small gas masses.
 It is less clear why the WeakFB produces a small obscured fraction.
 Presumably the feedback is not sufficient to vertically puff up galaxies,
 thereby reducing covering fractions.
 However, these variations can be excluded based on their mismatch with
 other observations, e.g.
 the SMF 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "their Figure 10"
key "Crain2015"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next we discuss the effects of feedback from accreting SMBHs.
 In the EAGLE simulation, three parameters affect the triggering, efficiency
 and impact of AGN feedback respectively.
 The equation of state of the ISM can be modified from its reference value
 (4/3) to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 (
\family typewriter
eos1
\family default
).
 The increased sound speed then increases the accretion onto black holes
 in the simulation, which increases AGN feedback.
 Once near the black hole, matter is placed into the black hole with a Bondi
 accretion formula modified by a viscosity parameter.
 Increasing the viscosity (
\family typewriter
ViscHi
\family default
) allows gas to loose angular momentum and accrete more efficiently.
 Once accreted, the temperature of particles near AGN is increased by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta T=10^{8.5}{\rm K}$
\end_inset

, stochastically, bringing the gas into the metal cooling regime.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Schaye2015"

\end_inset

 test the impact of increasing this temperature to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta T=10^{9}{\rm K}$
\end_inset

 (
\family typewriter
AGNdT9
\family default
).
 Each of these three modification (
\family typewriter
eos1
\family default
, 
\family typewriter
ViscHi
\family default
, 
\family typewriter
AGNdT9
\family default
) leads to a reduction of the obscured fraction of AGN (see Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:gasobscprofile-many"

\end_inset

), while contrary modifications (
\family typewriter
eos5/3
\family default
, 
\family typewriter
ViscLo
\family default
, 
\family typewriter
AGNdT8
\family default
) do the opposite.
 It is worth noting that 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Schaye2015"

\end_inset

 preferred the 
\family typewriter
AGNdT9
\family default
 variation over the reference simulation because it better fits soft X-ray
 observations of cluster gas.
 We also point out that Illustris uses relative strong feedback, as it implement
s three different AGN feedback schemes (thermal, kinetic and radiation),
 whereas EAGLE uses only stochastic heating.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
AGN outflows or radiation pressure may decrease the covering fractions momentari
ly.
 We have so far considered 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 simulated galaxies and found that they produce high covering fractions.
 Arguably these fractions are consistent with the covering fraction of low-lumin
osity AGN.
 Therefore, one could propose that AGN feedback at high luminosities modifies
 the galaxy in such way that covering fractions are reduced.
 Apriori this proposal appears unlikely, because nuclear gas should be affected
 first.
 Additionally, studies comparing the morphology of active and passive galaxies
 have found little evidence that these are different, by comparing appearances
 with asymmetry and concentration measures 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Grogin2003,Grogin2005,Pierce2007,Gabor2009,Kocevski2012"

\end_inset

 or visual classification 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kocevski2012"

\end_inset

.
 Indeed, our results remain unchanged if in the EAGLE reference simulation
 we only consider simulated galaxies with instantaneous black hole accretion
 rates corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $L(2-10\,{\rm keV})>10^{42}{\rm erg/s}$
\end_inset

, assuming a radiative efficiency of 10% and bolometric corrections of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Marconi2004"

\end_inset

.
 In fact, because active galaxies are preferentially gas-rich, star-forming
 galaxies in that simulation, the average column density is higher by a
 factor of 2, which increases the discrepancy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clumpy ISM may decrease the covering fractions.
 For instance the galactic ISM is structured into parsec-size clumps with
 filling factors of 
\begin_inset Formula $1\%$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cox2005"

\end_inset

.
 Such clumps could not be resolved by simulations.
 However, as a LOS passes through large distances of the ISM (
\begin_inset Formula $1-\text{few}$
\end_inset

 kiloparsecs), this clumpiness averages out.
 Additionally, clumpiness would effectively only redistribute the obscured
 fraction to both lower and higher column densities, potentially violating
 the constraints of higher column densities.
 There are also differences in the hydrodynamics code schemes and their
 accuracy.
 However, these are less important than the chosen sub-grid models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "J. Shaye, priv. comm., see"
key "Scannapieco2012,Schaller2015,Cui2016,Sembolini2016"

\end_inset

 in the present non-classical SPH simulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To summarise, our obscured fraction diagnostic is a highly sensitive test
 of feedback recipes.
 It can easily rule out feedback models already at early times (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $z=3$
\end_inset

) in the simulations, if they produce very high fractions of obscured AGN.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Summary"

\end_inset

Using only observational relations, we predict the covering fractions of
 galaxy-scale gas as relevant for the AGN population.
 Our findings can be summarised as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Galaxy-scale gas does not provide Compton-thick lines of sight.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Galaxy-scale gas covers substantial fractions of the SMBH population at
 
\begin_inset Formula $\NH\approx10^{22-23.5}{\rm cm}^{-2}$
\end_inset

, sufficient to explain the observed luminosity-independent baseline obscuration.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We therefore conclude that heavily obscured AGN are associated with nuclear
 obscuration, and propose the value 
\begin_inset Formula $\NH=10^{23.5}{\rm cm}^{-2}$
\end_inset

 as a demarcation line singling out the nuclear obscurer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We subtracted the galaxy-scale obscuration and concluded regarding the remaining
 nuclear obscurer, that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
a nuclear Compton-thick obscurer with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim35\%$
\end_inset

 covering is necessary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
a nuclear Compton-thin obscurer is necessary for some combinations of luminosity
/black hole mass.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The result is formalised into a semi-analytic model for cosmological simulations
, called PuffedTorus (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:PuffedTorus"

\end_inset

).
 The cartoon of Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Cartoon"

\end_inset

 illustrates a possible physical scenario for these three, distinct obscuring
 components.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also investigated the inside of simulated galaxies from state-of-the-art
 hydro-dynamic, cosmological simulations and apply ray-tracing from their
 black holes.
 Some of these simulations produce obscured fractions from their metal gas
 which is consistent with observed populations.
 However, the results are highly sensitive to the adopted feedback models
 and therefore lack predictive power.
 We therefore suggest the Compton-thin obscured AGN fraction as a diagnostic
 to rule out feedback models.
 This diagnostic which can be applied already at early cosmic times (
\begin_inset Formula $z=2-3$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

