\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:semi-analytic"

\end_inset

Important constraints on how much gas resides in galaxies can be drawn from
 cosmological simulations.
 Such simulations evolve the matter density available at the Big Bang into
 collapsing bound structures.
 Semi-analytic models, relying on dark matter haloes from dark matter N-body
 simulations have been highly successful in reproducing many features of
 galaxies, including the stellar mass function of galaxies and their colour
 distribution 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Croton2006,Somerville2008,Hirschmann2012,Fanidakis2012"

\end_inset

.
 As an illustrative case, we consider the model of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Croton2016"

\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:MZ-sam"

\end_inset

 plots the metal gas mass (the X-ray obscurer) present as a function of
 galaxy stellar mass.
 The median (red curve) falls consistently in the 1:30 to 1:100 range for
 the ratio of metal gas mass to stellar mass.
 With AGN host galaxies primarily drawn around the 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\star}=10^{10-11}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

 regime, the total gas available to obscure a central point source is about
 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\text{Z}}\sim10^{9}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

.
 The Illustris simulation shows very similar results at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1-3$
\end_inset

 obeying the same gas ratios.
 However at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

, the high-mass end is lacks gas due to the strong feedback implemented
 in that simulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
