\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:sim-MZ-obsc"

\end_inset

X-ray obscuration a given metal gas mass can reach.
 A obscurer of column density 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{H}$
\end_inset

 outside a radius 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 has a minimum metal gas mass limit 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{Z}$
\end_inset

 (lines).
 For example, a 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{Z}=10^{9}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

 gas mass has to be brought withing 100pc to completely enshroud a region
 with Compton-thick column densities.
 Keep in mind that such masses are only found in very massive galaxies (
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\star}>3\cdot10^{10}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

, see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:MZ-sam"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

We present a simple calculation to show that Compton-thick column densities,
 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\NH>1.5\times10^{24}\text{cm}^{-2}$
\end_inset

) cannot be achieved by accumulating the galaxy gas over several kpc.
 In X-ray spectral analysis, the equivalent hydrogen column density 
\begin_inset Formula $\NH$
\end_inset

 is usually computed assuming solar abundances.
 To mimic this, we convert the metal mass in particles to the number of
 hydrogen atoms assuming solar mass fractions of the nearby ISM from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Wilms2000"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
n_{\text{H}} & = & \left.\frac{f_{\text{X}}}{f_{\text{Z}}}\right|_{\text{solar}}\times\frac{\rho_{\text{Z}}}{m_{\text{H}}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Inserting numbers including the hydrogen mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\text{H}}$
\end_inset

 we find 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
n_{\text{H}} & = & 0.737\times10^{22}\text{cm}^{-2}\frac{1}{1\text{kpc}}\times\frac{\rho_{\text{Z}}}{10^{6}M_{\odot}\text{kpc}^{-3}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

For example, a 1kpc ray in a region of metal gas density 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{6}M_{\odot}/\text{kpc}^{3}$
\end_inset

 results in a measured column density of 
\begin_inset Formula $\NH\approx10^{22}\text{cm}^{-2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The gas inside a galaxy may be arranged in a multitude of ways to achieve
 a covering with column density 
\begin_inset Formula $\NH$
\end_inset

.
 If we consider only gas 
\emph on
outside
\emph default
 a certain radius 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, the most effective obscurer, i.e.
 the one with the least mass but complete covering, is an infinitely thin
 shell at that radius 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Its mass is easily computed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{\text{H}}(\NH,>R)=4\pi\cdot R^{2}\times\NH\times m_{\text{H}}.
\]

\end_inset

Converting to metals using the factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\left.\frac{f_{\text{Z}}}{f_{\text{X}}}\right|_{\text{solar}}$
\end_inset

and expressing in conventional units, this limit is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{\text{Z}}(\NH,>R)=2.6\times10^{9}M_{\odot}\cdot\frac{\NH}{1.5\times10^{24}\text{cm}^{-2}}\cdot\left(\frac{R}{1\text{kpc}}\right)^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore, a metal mass larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $2.6\times10^{9}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

 is required to create a Compton-thick obscurer outside the central 
\begin_inset Formula $1\text{kpc}$
\end_inset

.
 Or equivalently, a metal mass of 
\begin_inset Formula $2.6\times10^{9}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

 has to be brought to the central 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{kpc}$
\end_inset

 to act as a Compton-thick obscurer.
 Note that this mass limit scales with the covering factor; for example
 obscuration of 
\begin_inset Formula $10\%$
\end_inset

 of the sky requires 
\begin_inset Formula $10\%$
\end_inset

 of the mass.
 This simple limit is shown for several levels of obscuration in Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sim-MZ-obsc"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Risaliti1999"

\end_inset

 already noted that such large masses at radii further than a few 10 pc
 are ruled out in NGC1068 and Circinus because they would gravitationally
 dominate the central region.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining this simple limit with the masses of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:MZ-sam"

\end_inset

, we can now conclude that galaxies lack the gas required for Compton-thick
 obscuration with substantial covering factors outside the central 
\begin_inset Formula $1\text{kpc}$
\end_inset

.
 Admittedly, this is a weak constraint.
 However the result holds independently of the geometry of the gas, the
 galaxy type and is also applicable to mergers.
 As an example, lets consider that a 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\star}=10^{9}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

 merges into a 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\star}=10^{10}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

 galaxy (minor merger), and lets assume that all of its gas (
\begin_inset Formula $M_{Z}\approx10^{7}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

) is made available.
 That entire amount of gas must land within 
\begin_inset Formula $100{\rm pc}$
\end_inset

 of the AGN in order to completely enshroud in Compton-thick columns.
 More quantitative conclusions depend on the geometrical distribution of
 the gas in the galaxy.
 We analyse the galaxies produced by hydrodynamic simulations in Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Cosmological-simulations"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

